'''振荡'''（{{lang-en|Oscillation}}）指某一可观测量的值关于中心值（常为平衡点）往复变化，或可观测量在两个态或多个态之间往复变化，常指随时间的变化。常见的例子是[[单摆|单摆]]和[[交流电|交流电]]。振荡也常称作[[振动|振动]]，虽然二者作为同义词交叉使用，但振动常指机械振荡。振荡不仅仅出现在物理系统中，也會出现在[[生态学|生物系统]]中，包括人类[[社会|社会]]和[[神经振荡|大脑]]。

通过[[周期|周期]]性的状态改变，系统按照固定的[[时间|时间]][[微分|微分]]重复变化的末态。总的来说：振荡是一个与[[时间|时间]]相关的[[物理|物理]]状态参数。

这样来说，对于力学、电学或者[[液体|液体]]状态量有：
*力学状态参数：延展、振动速度、振动加速度、振动角、[[角速度|角速度]]、[[角加速度|角加速度]]、[[力|力]]、[[力矩|力矩]]
*电学状态参数：[[电流|电流]]、[[电压|电压]]、[[功率|功率]]、[[电荷|电荷]]、[[电感|电感]]、[[电容|电容]]、[[电阻|电阻]]
*液体状态参数：[[体积|体积]]、[[压强|压强]]、[[速度|速度]]、[[密度|密度]]、[[落差|落差]]

==简谐振子==
{{Main|简谐运动}}
<!-- 

The simplest mechanical oscillating system is a [[mass|mass]] attached to a [[linear|linear]] [[spring_(device)|spring]] subject to only [[weight|weight]] and [[Tension_(physics)|tension]].  Such a system may be approximated on an air table or ice surface.  The system is in an [[mechanical_equilibrium|equilibrium]] state when the spring is static. If the system is displaced from the equilibrium, there is a net ''restoring force'' on the mass, tending to bring it back to equilibrium.  However, in moving the mass back to the equilibrium position, it has acquired [[momentum|momentum]] which keeps it moving beyond that position, establishing a new restoring force in the opposite sense.  If a constant [[force|force]] such as [[gravity|gravity]] is added to the system, the point of equilibrium is shifted.  The time taken for an oscillation to occur is often referred to as the oscillatory ''period''.

Systems where the restoring force on a body is directly proportional to its displacement, such as the [[dynamics_(mechanics)|dynamics]] of the spring-mass system, are described mathematically by the [[Harmonic_oscillator#Simple_harmonic_oscillator|simple harmonic oscillator]] and the regular [[period_(physics)|periodic]] motion is known as [[simple_harmonic_motion|simple harmonic motion]].  In the spring-mass system, oscillations occur because, at the [[statics|static]] equilibrium displacement, the mass has [[kinetic_energy|kinetic energy]] which is converted into [[potential_energy|potential energy]] stored in the spring at the extremes of its path.  The spring-mass system illustrates some common features of oscillation, namely the existence of an equilibrium and the presence of a restoring force which grows stronger the further the system deviates from equilibrium.

